1882_07-21_Seymour-Record

OXFORD

Services both morning and afternoon in St. Peter's church next Sunday, with Holy Communion in a.m.

The funeral of Mrs. Lucinda Davis was attended from the house and church on Thursday afternoon, Rev. Mr. Bailey officiating.

The funeral of Miss Jennie J. Hotchkiss was largely attended from the house and church on Saturday, the 15th, Revs. Potwine and Bailey officiating.

Mrs. N. D. Baldwin of Birmingham, who has been ill for some time, has become suddenly worse while on a visit at David Hawley's and is not able to return home.

The mortality here has been unusual during the present month, four persons having died since the 4th, three of whom lived on Chestnut-tree Hill within a mile, at the average age of 75.

On Monday, the 17th, Louie a nine year old son of F. L. Davis, was badly eat on the back of both legs, just above the ankle, by a scythe in the hands of a younger lad, son of Phillip Schwartz.

